<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">I'm currently a 35th Shaman and I must say that the volume of sow requests I recieve daily have not diminished by the least since the day I turned 9.<br>
 <br>
      Okay so I don't mind helping out people, infact I enjoy it. Nevertheless, I'm starting to learn the magic of a simple reply, "No." People hate it yet some situations warrant it. People have hissy fits. People /rude you and try to make some dull witted sarcastic remark that will boost their self inflated false sense of ego as well as allowing them to leave feeling that they came out on top. "No" can come to be quite satisfying but don't be too generous with your "No"'s. If someone actually puts some effort into their preposition, such as asking in a complete and semi-well thought out sentence, a SoW is a generous reward. <p>

 -The Philosophy of "No"-<br>
     Lets put together the hypothetical situation that all of us SoW dealers see daily. Guy comes up and stares at you for a moment. We already know exactly what he wants because no random person just walks up and stares at you like that for a good 10 seconds. At this magical moment it becomes evident that this fine creature that stands before you is doing some stratigic hunt-n-peck typing... putting together a highly structured and well thought out phrase that will make us overflow with the generousity, enough to want to help out this creatively endowed charismatic individual. What might they ask us? Drum roll......."sow plz". Ah! So they've mustered together enough effort to actually type those six letters. You've got to give it to them. They Really know how to get what they want. I better be quite serving of their extraordinary efforts to painstakingly walk up and type this. On the other hand, if I don't provide, I know they may exercise their right to practice their shift-up arrow-enter-and-repeat skills (just in case I didn't catch what they were asking the first or the ninth time). For some reason this scenario always conjures the image of a male dwarf clothed in all bronze into my mind. <p>

       Anyways, what I think I'm saying is that if you want a sow just ask politely in a well thought out way. For every action there is an opposite and equal reaction. Put a little energy into it and it may bounce back in your direction and in the desired form (such as a sow). Ask in a complete sentence. Don't do a /tell from the other side of the zone requesting the sow at your desired location and in your desired time frame without some sort of compensation. Don't ask for the sow when we're in the middle of a heated battle. Don't take it for granted and don't be an a-hole or else that's the same treatement you'll be given in return<p>

"Just my 2cp" I think that's how it goes<br>
Grohm<br>
35th Shaman of Barbaric blood - Karana</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
